84-year-old man is transferred from his nursing home to the Emergency Department with a two-day history of colicky abdominal pain, constipation and abdominal distension. He has never had any similar symptoms before. His medical history includes atrial fibrillation, hypertension, and benign prostatic hyperplasia. He is on apixaban and perindopril. He had an appendicectomy at the age of 50 and a transurethral resection of the prostate at the age of 72.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination his observations are within normal limits and his abdomen is uniformly distended and soft with mild diffuse tenderness. His rectum is empty. Plain abdominal X-rays are performed (image 1, 2).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["CT scan abdomen","Bladder catheterisation and nasogastric tube","Sigmoidoscopy and flatus tube","Gastrograffin enema","Laparotomy"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis is the classical scenario of a sigmoid volvulus, both in terms of the clinical presentation and the radiological findings. The X-rays show a large loop of sigmoid colon rising out of the pelvis. This is often referred to as \u0027coffee bean\u0027 sign. In developed countries this condition is relatively unusual and typically occurs in elderly nursing home residents and is presumably related to chronic constipation. Sigmoid volvulus is seen more frequently in certain developing countries, where diet probably plays a central role in its aetiology.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe next step in management should be to achieve decompression. This can usually be done with by \u003Cstrong\u003Esigmoidoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E, which is first-line management for sigmoid volvulus. Once the volvulus is de-torted, a rectal tube can be inserted to maintain decompression and further action (surgery) considered.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGiven the history and radiological findings which all point to a clinical diagnosis of sigmoid volvulus, \u003Cstrong\u003ECT scan\u003C/strong\u003E is unlikely to provide any further clarification regarding diagnosis. It may be useful in a suspected perforation; however, given this patient\u0027s abdominal examination is not indicative of perforation and peritonitis, this is unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBladder catheterisation\u003C/strong\u003E is useful in the treatment of urinary retention, which is unlikely to be the cause of this patient\u0027s pain given the history and x-ray findings as described. A \u003Cstrong\u003Enasogastric tube \u003C/strong\u003Ewill be ineffective in decompressing a sigmoid volvulus. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlthough \u003Cstrong\u003Egastrograffin enema\u003C/strong\u003E has been used historically for the treatment of sigmoid volvulus, it has a lower success rate than rigid sigmoidoscopy, and is no longer routinely used when sigmoidoscopy is available.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELaparotomy\u003C/strong\u003E is reserved for patients who fail to be successfully treated by sigmoidoscopy, or in cases of non-viable or perforated colon. This patient has no signs of perforation and is fit for sigmoidoscopy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["\u0027Coffee bean\u0027 sign on abdominal x-ray is pathognomonic for sigmoid volvulus.","First-line treatment for sigmoid volvulus is a rigid sigmoidoscopy."],"references":["Clinical Practice Guidelines for Colon Volvulus and Acute Colonic Pseudo-Obstruction. (2016) Diseases of the Colon \u0026 Rectum. 59 (7): 589. doi:10.1097/DCR.0000000000000602 - Pubmed","Salati U, Mcneill G, Torreggiani WC. The coffee bean sign in sigmoid volvulus. Radiology. 2011;258 (2): 651-2."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35756"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"530"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media"